      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you engage in a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) workout, your muscles are working harder than usual, and they start to produce lactic acid as a byproduct. It's like your muscles are trying to keep up with the demands of the workout, and lactic acid is the way they signal that they're under stress. The body then has to deal with this lactic acid, which is a bit like a pesky little goblin that just won't leave.\n\nAfter the workout, your body starts to clear out the lactic acid. This happens through a process called the Cori cycle, where the lactic acid is transported to the liver and converted back into glucose, which can then be used for energy. It's like the body is sending a team of goblins to clean up the mess and make sure everything is back to normal. So, in essence, the lactic acid is a temporary byproduct of intense exercise, and the body has its own way of dealing with it, ensuring that you're ready for the next round of goblin-like challenges.",
